==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|rumour}} (UK, Commonwealth, International)

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|rumour}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|fro|rumeur}}, from {{der|en|la|rūmor|t=common talk}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈɹuːmə(ɹ)/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈɹumɚ/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|uːmə(r)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|US|countable}} A [[statement]] or [[claim]] of [[questionable]] [[accuracy]], from no known [[reliable]] source, usually spread by [[word of mouth]].
#: ''There's a '''rumor''' going round that he's going to get married.''
# {{lb|en|US|uncountable}} [[information|Information]] or [[misinformation]] of the kind contained in such claims.
#: ''They say he used to be a thief, but that's just '''rumor'''.''

